  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, invisible barrier that affects my own experience as a young woman navigating academic challenges. Growing up in Rome with parents who have vastly different educational backgrounds—my mother with only lower secondary education and my father a PhD holder—has shaped my perspective on how stereotypes can influence someone's performance. I've noticed that when I enter STEM discussions, even in my upper secondary classes, I sometimes feel the weight of assumptions about women being less capable in technical fields. This isn't just about confidence; it's about the psychological toll of knowing that my presence might confirm a stereotype. As someone who struggles with depression and has a low openness to new experiences, I find it particularly hard to engage in conversations where I might be perceived as 'not fitting in.' Addressing stereotype threat requires more than just awareness—it needs systemic changes in how we design educational environments. For example, teacher training should focus on creating inclusive classrooms where students feel safe to make mistakes without fear of judgment. I've seen how small gestures, like acknowledging diverse strengths and encouraging collaboration, can make a big difference. In my volunteering work with youth groups, I've noticed that when students are given space to explore their interests without pressure to conform to gender norms, their confidence grows. It's crucial that we address stereotype threat early, especially for young people like me who are already dealing with mental health challenges. Without intervention, the cycle of underperformance and self-doubt can continue, limiting opportunities for those who could thrive in STEM.",
